description:
## Description

Even if the BE isn't ready for it, let's use Rails to send the query parameters instead of parsing the URL from the FE.

## Context

The following discussion from !30560 should be addressed:

- [ ] @pslaughter started a [discussion](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/merge_requests/30560#note_338612897): 

    > **suggesting (non-blocking):** Based on the conversation in https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/merge_requests/30560#note_337759366, it sounds like these values should and will eventually come from the BE. In hindsight, anytime we read from the URL in the FE, we should probably stop and pass these params through rails instead (since Rails is technically the owner of the routing responsibility).
    > 
    > Even if the BE isn't completely ready to support and parse these values, we can still iterate towards this by using `request.query_params`. This keeps our FE decoupled from routing and URL parsing from the get go:
    > 
    > ```patch
    > diff --git a/app/assets/javascripts/monitoring/monitoring_bundle.js b/app/assets/javascripts/monitoring/monitoring_bundle.js
    > index c2c1ceab312..f6ced5de5b1 100644
    > --- a/app/assets/javascripts/monitoring/monitoring_bundle.js
    > +++ b/app/assets/javascripts/monitoring/monitoring_bundle.js
    > @@ -4,7 +4,7 @@ import Dashboard from '~/monitoring/components/dashboard.vue';
    >  import { parseBoolean } from '~/lib/utils/common_utils';
    >  import { getParameterValues } from '~/lib/utils/url_utility';
    >  import store from './stores';
    > -import { promCustomVariablesFromUrl } from './utils';
    > +import { promCustomVariables } from './utils';
    >  
    >  Vue.use(GlToast);
    >  
    > @@ -13,8 +13,10 @@ export default (props = {}) => {
    >  
    >    if (el && el.dataset) {
    >      const [currentDashboard] = getParameterValues('dashboard');
    > +    const { promVariablesJson } = el.dataset;
    > +    const promVariables = promVariablesJson ? JSON.parse(promVariablesJson) : {};
    >  
    > -    store.dispatch('monitoringDashboard/setVariables', promCustomVariablesFromUrl());
    > +    store.dispatch('monitoringDashboard/setVariables', promCustomVariables(promVariables));
    >  
    >      // eslint-disable-next-line no-new
    >      new Vue({
    > diff --git a/app/assets/javascripts/monitoring/utils.js b/app/assets/javascripts/monitoring/utils.js
    > index 45db2208d66..7d0eb4afe82 100644
    > --- a/app/assets/javascripts/monitoring/utils.js
    > +++ b/app/assets/javascripts/monitoring/utils.js
    > @@ -129,8 +129,7 @@ export const timeRangeFromUrl = (search = window.location.search) => {
    >   * @param {String} New URL
    >   */
    >  
    > -export const promCustomVariablesFromUrl = (search = window.location.search) => {
    > -  const params = queryToObject(search);
    > +export const promCustomVariables = (params = {}) => {
    >    const paramsToRemove = timeRangeParamNames.concat(dashboardParams);
    >  
    >    return omit(params, paramsToRemove);
    > diff --git a/app/helpers/environments_helper.rb b/app/helpers/environments_helper.rb
    > index 21b2111baf7..52d83e570ec 100644
    > --- a/app/helpers/environments_helper.rb
    > +++ b/app/helpers/environments_helper.rb
    > @@ -47,7 +47,8 @@ module EnvironmentsHelper
    >        "validate-query-path" => validate_query_project_prometheus_metrics_path(project),
    >        "custom-metrics-available" => "#{custom_metrics_available?(project)}",
    >        "alerts-endpoint" => project_prometheus_alerts_path(project, environment_id: environment.id, format: :json),
    > -      "prometheus-alerts-available" => "#{can?(current_user, :read_prometheus_alerts, project)}"
    > +      "prometheus-alerts-available" => "#{can?(current_user, :read_prometheus_alerts, project)}",
    > +      "prom-variables-json" => request.query_parameters.to_json
    >      }
    >    end 
    > 
    > ```
    > 
    > This also makes testing our utility function a lot easier!
    > 
    > IMHO, this isn't a blocker, but it would be great to follow up with this in another MR sooner than later :point_up:
